   Tee   1.","Jewish (from Poland): metonymic occupational name for a tea merchant, from central Yiddish <i>tay</i> ‘tea’."],"variants":[{"name":"Tays","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Tay  ."]},{"name":"Tee","meanings":["English: variant of   Tye  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 鄭, see   Zheng   1.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 池, possibly based on its Hokkien or Teochew pronunciation, see   Chi   1."]},{"name":"Taye","meanings":["Ethiopian: from the personal name <i>Taye</i>, which is interpreted as ‘he was seen’ in the Amharic language. — Note: Since Ethiopians do not have hereditary surnames, this name was registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US.","English (mainly Middlesex): variant of   Tay   1. This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Amelia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A blend of two medieval names: <i>Emilia</i> (which is of Latin origin:  see  Emily  ) and the Latinized Germanic   Amalia .   Henry Fielding  is sometimes credited with having coined it for the heroine of his novel Amelia (  1751 ), but forms such as <i>Meelia</i>, <i>Amaly</i> and <i>Aemelia</i> occur from the 17th century onwards."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Amelia Tay was born in 1422, in Long Stanton, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John Tay, was 21 and her mother, Lady Mary Margerie Smith, was 17. She married Thomas Burgoyne in 1442, in Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 4 daughters. She died in 1457, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1422–1457":"1422–1457","1423–1457":"1423–1457","1443–1500":"1443–1500","1451–Female":"1451–Surnud","1452–Female":"1452–Surnud","1453–1502":"1453–1502","1457–Female":"1457–Surnud","1401–1470":"1401–1470","1405–1432":"1405–1432","1451":"1451","1470":"1470","1502":"1502","1457":"1457","1401":"1401","1500":"1500","1423":"1423","1422":"1422","1432":"1432","1443":"1443","1442":"1442","1453":"1453","about 1457":"umbes 1457","1452":"1452","about 1443":"umbes 1443","about 1452":"umbes 1452","1405":"1405","Longstanton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Long Stanton, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"1422–1457":"1422–1457","1423–1457":"1423–1457","1443–1500":"1443–1500","1451–Female":"1451–Kuollut","1452–Female":"1452–Kuollut","1453–1502":"1453–1502","1457–Female":"1457–Kuollut","1401–1470":"1401–1470","1405–1432":"1405–1432","1451":"1451","1470":"1470","1502":"1502","1457":"1457","1401":"1401","1500":"1500","1423":"1423","1422":"1422","1432":"1432","1443":"1443","1442":"1442","1453":"1453","about 1457":"noin 1457","1452":"1452","about 1443":"noin 1443","about 1452":"noin 1452","1405":"1405","Longstanton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Long Stanton, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Cambri